80,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-13 05:51:29+00:00,55258005,jopohl/urh,18219846,jopohl,,,213631366,286020976,"Hi @gustavecha 

problem with RTL-SDR is, that different sticks support different gains. There is an API method to get the gains available on a stick, which produces this for my device:
```
[0, 9, 14, 27, 37, 77, 87, 125, 144, 157, 166, 197, 207, 229, 254, 280, 297, 328, 338, 364, 372, 386, 402, 421, 434, 439, 445, 480, 496]
```
Note, that all gain values are calculated *10. This is the way, the RTL-SDR API demands and outputs them.

Here you can also see the reason for your described jumpy behaviour: If I put the gain in my example e.g. from 30 (mapped to 27) to 32 (mapped to 37 by API) I experience a much larger jump, than I  would expect. The certain limits may vary from device to device.

A solution for this is to ask the user for an index in above gain array and not the exact gain value. This is the way, that SDR# goes. However, as @andynoack pointed out, this would conflict with the usability for other SDRs in URH. 

I am open for suggestions on this.",{},,User,False
