109,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-30 09:03:34+00:00,27924304,cdent/gabbi,3515,FND,,,98091193,126233439,"It's actually your ""that would get noisy with long bodies (especially binary ones)"" statement that prompted this idea. Using a file rather than STDOUT would avoid having to identify and extract the body from surrounding output, plus it eliminates the risk ruining your TTY with binary data. It would also allow for easily inspecting multiple bodies in one go by creating separate files. (Obviously any file descriptor should be valid, so you might also use STDERR and redirect that on the shell.)

> that verbose setting is getting pretty verbose itself [...] it is adding noise to the test

Yeah, I didn't want to get into that before, but:

* I'd assumed that `verbose` is almost always used for debugging, i.e. not persisted - thus it would only be temporary and localized noise, which isn't so bad.
* Since the above structures can be annoying to type over and over again during debugging, we'd probably _also_ need a shorthand (with `verbose: 2` being the obvious choice).

Obviously the latter kind of challenges the existence of a verbose structure in the first place. I can't _really_ explain why I like having an explicit version (in particular because there's probably never gonna be a `verbose: 3`, since there's nothing else in HTTP interactions that should be relevant) - except perhaps that it seems easier to learn (first introducing the longhand, then mentioned ""oh btw, there's a shorthand too). Of course the shorthand version doesn't allow for custom files either.",{},,User,False
