audio_outfile = '/Users/justin/Downloads/trimtest_out.wav'
```
and if you no longer care about audio_infile after processing, you can os.remove(audio_infile).

Ehm, well, I'm of course aware that I can do this, but that's not my use case ;) My use case requires overwriting the same file. Saving the output file into a separate directory is exactly what the snippet I included in my first post does (and then copies it over and overwrites the input file). But I feel like that's besides the point - regardless of whether one prefers to keep their input/output files separate or not, right now the user *can* provide the same filepath for input/output and pysox *will* spit out an invalid audio file without any warning, which is undocumented behavior and, I think, undesirable.",{},,User,False
