1612,IssueCommentEvent,2017-08-14 08:07:16+00:00,27283062,ktbyers/netmiko,10410757,wisotzky,,,249853561,322125468,"Actually I came across this while building a new NAPALM driver for Nokia routers (running SR OS). My issue is, that when implementing the NAPALM method _load_replace_candidate()_ and calling line by line the netmiko _send_command()_ the performance is really bad.
The issue is likely related to the fact, that I am based in Frankfurt/Germany while my VSRs are in Canada - so round-trip latency is almost 200ms. Therefore, even in theory I can not get more than 5 commands/second. Realistically napalm/netmiko and SR OS do consume quite some extra-time by themselves - so overall performance is much worse than 5 instructions per second.

Having this said, cross-checking with the NAPALM implementation for Cisco IOS, they are transferring the configuration to merge/replace using SCP (or something calling inline file-transfer). This is much more efficient, because it comes down to TCP performance (based on TCP window-size/ACK) - which is much more efficient. Finally the configuration is processed locally on the router.

I would like to have a very similar implementation for Nokia SR OS. But the issue is, that the class FileTransfer is designed for Cisco IOS only. Clearly it should work to inherit the class and overwrite some of the methods to make it work with other routers. Anyhow, it would be good to have a similar mechanism like the _napalm.get_network_driver(""myRouterOS"")_ to instantiate a router/vendor specific FileTransfer object.",{},,User,False
