2019,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-08 15:49:55+00:00,20101515,giampaolo/psutil,681260,giampaolo,,,317802661,387449997,If you read the doc you'll notice how that is Linux only for now. =),{},OWNER,User,False
2022,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-16 10:06:55+00:00,20101515,giampaolo/psutil,681260,giampaolo,,,331611460,397802437,"What do you mean about the GIL is at fault? 

As for the error you're seeing, it almost certainly originates from here:
https://github.com/giampaolo/psutil/blob/ac9dccab6b038835b5d612f92cf4804ec2662c2e/psutil/_psutil_windows.c#L1544-L1548
And this is where it's translated into a MemoryError exception:
https://github.com/giampaolo/psutil/blob/ac9dccab6b038835b5d612f92cf4804ec2662c2e/psutil/_psutil_windows.c#L1707-L1712

Since it's `malloc()` which fails I suppose that means you run out of physical memory. How much RAM does your system have and how many connections were reported by `psutil.net_connections(kind='all')` before it failed? You can try something like this:

```
try:
    print(len(psutil.net_connections(kind='all')))
except MemoryError:
    print(psutil.virtual_memory())
```

To conduct test I recommend `psutil.net_connections(kind='all')` instead of `psutil.Process().connections(kind=""tcp4"")` (both use the same C function anyway). ",{},OWNER,User,False
