2279,IssueCommentEvent,2018-04-26 09:28:38+00:00,112461400,axnsan12/drf-yasg,6382979,axnsan12,,,317942637,384575194,"Both additions would be welcome 😄 

An integration with ``django-rest-framework-recursive``  similar to [the one with ``djangorestframework-camel-case``](https://github.com/axnsan12/drf-yasg/blob/master/src/drf_yasg/inspectors/field.py#L493) would do no harm.

Refactoring the ref_name logic into a method would also make that integration cleaner and help maintenance down the road, so great!

Regarding your code:

```python
            definitions = ReferenceResolver(openapi.SCHEMA_DEFINITIONS).with_scope(openapi.SCHEMA_DEFINITIONS)
            definitions.set(ref_name, openapi.Schema(type=openapi.TYPE_OBJECT))

            return openapi.SchemaRef(definitions, ref_name)
```

I assume this is the hack you were talking about, which you had to do because of [this assert](https://github.com/axnsan12/drf-yasg/blob/d2dc09cb3c765938af32e3c0dcda2e2b31140721/src/drf_yasg/openapi.py#L481), since the serializer you're trying to reference doesn't exist yet.

I think just removing that assertion would be ok, since there may be other cases where one would want a 'forward' reference to a type. Wrong references should be caught by validators at the end anyways, so error checking would not be affected too much.

",{},OWNER,User,False
