2608,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-28 20:17:34+00:00,78548891,rm-hull/luma.core,1915543,rm-hull,,,203232132,283149358,"Looking into this, the Raspberry Pi _and/or_ the BCM2835 chipset _and/or_ the Linux kernel doesn't properly support 9 bits-per-word SPI, quoting http://librpip.frasersdev.net/peripheral-config/spi/:

> Despite the Broadcom 2835 ARM Peripherals document (p150) discussing multiple transfer sizes including 9bit ‘Lossi’  – commonly used by LCD screens – however when the device is queried it only supports 8bit transfers. This is a real pity. Perhaps someone can explain that to me.

Other sites suggest the same, https://github.com/doceme/py-spidev/issues/6:

> I'm having the same problem using the Raspberry Pi as SPI master, it has been a tremendous headache.
As you can see in the RPi wiki web page, the Raspberry Pi only supports 8 bits per word
http://elinux.org/RPi_SPI

Indeed, trying [spidev_test](https://github.com/rm-hull/spidev-test) confirms this:

    $ ./spidev_test --device /dev/spidev0.0 --bpw 9
    can't set bits per word: Invalid argument

So closing this as won't fix, (untested) code changes are in commit dedb08f",{},,User,False
