2946,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-31 23:42:36+00:00,5186662,renatopp/liac-arff,78827,jnothman,,,346021762,409402705,"I don't find having a plethora of fine-grained syntax error exception types helpful.

There's a reason why Python only has, I think, two distinct syntax error types (SyntaxError, IndentationError): once there is a error in the syntax, it's very hard to definitively describe what went wrong. Presuming the intention of the user (e.g. that they failed to quote a multi-token nominal) is not really helpful.

It's much easier to provide a fast parser if it does not worry about keeping track of the kind of state needed to discriminate between many types of error; while that can be done by re-running a more diagnostic parser in case of error, I don't see why we would want to engineer that.

Can I please propose that we have one or two syntax errors, and then a type casting error, and that's it?",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
