2985,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-21 15:28:56+00:00,6794278,scanny/python-pptx,32445313,thoramgowtham,,,127960759,374979365,"Does this functionality added to the module?, I mean Adding or deleting a row from existing table. If yes how to do that? ",{},NONE,User,False
2986,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-26 09:28:26+00:00,6794278,scanny/python-pptx,2062718,scanny,,,266289892,339607317,"Ah, okay, I think I know what's happening now after a brief look through the code.

`Paragraph.text` transforms `'\n'` characters into `<a:br/>` elements, which render as ""soft"" line breaks. `Run.text` does not have that behavior, and inserts the new-line characters directly into the XML. You can see that in the second-to-last paragraph, where ""Use italics"" starts abruptly on a new line, not surrounded by element tags.

So it's going to be limited how you can work around that without writing workaround code to manipulate the XML directly. You can insert several runs separated by line feeds and then go back to them using `Paragraph.runs` to manipulate them individually, but you won't be able to format between line breaks.

In your position I think I would have a look at the code for `Paragraph.text` and maybe `Paragraph.add_run()` and use some of the internal `oxml` calls it uses to manipulate the XML. This is where all the action is for that it looks like: https://github.com/scanny/python-pptx/blob/master/pptx/oxml/text.py#L455

You might be able to accomplish what you want just using `paragraph._p.add_br()`. You could call that in-between adding runs to a paragraph when you wanted to insert a soft line break.

I'll leave this issue open as a feature request for `Paragraph.add_line_break()`.",{},OWNER,User,False
2987,IssueCommentEvent,2015-12-09 00:52:01+00:00,6794278,scanny/python-pptx,631015,jdgodchaux,,,24015573,163071944,@waveofbabies Did you have any luck with what @scanny proposed? Would you be willing to share what worked or didn't work? Thanks!,{},,User,False
2989,IssueCommentEvent,2016-01-30 05:11:06+00:00,6794278,scanny/python-pptx,2062718,scanny,,,118164361,177069379,"Hi @jaleskovec -- apologies it's taken me so long to get to this, just freed up from some other projects so have some time again to attend to it.

What I'll need for a start is to have the pull request in its own branch, say ""feature/stacked-charts"", based/rooted on the latest develop branch from scanny/python-pptx. That will probably take some rebasing on your side, but is the only way to get this merged cleanly without disrupting the commit history. I don't have enough experience with pull requests to know, but I think this will entail a new pull request because it will be a different branch. After that we should be able to add changes as required without creating new pull requests just by you rebasing in the same branch and the pushing that branch with the -f(orce) option.

Second, we should have an analysis page (that can be the first commit), that lays out the scope of what you're doing and outlines the changes and such. There are examples here:
http://python-pptx.readthedocs.org/en/latest/dev/analysis/features/cht-bar-chart.html

You can probably cut and paste most of the XML Schema bits from existing pages. They're located in docs/dev/analysis/features. There are a small collection of pages devoted to charts, so I expect this will be readily assembled mostly from bits and pieces there.

All we need is enough to understand how the stacked charts work, XML snippets that show the cases etc. I recommend making a quick draft with whatever you have off the top of your head and then I can ask for anything else I need. Once I understand how it works we'll be done with that bit.

The acceptance tests look pretty good. We'll need some added to features/cht-chart-props.feature to test that the .chart_type property correctly identifies known stacked charts, but we can get to that in due course.

There's likely to be a fair amount of rebasing to get the commits in order and parceled appropriately, so I'm hoping you're facile with `git rebase` :)  In particular, the analysis comes first, then the acceptance tests (marked @wip) in the next commit, then one commit for each atomic functionality bit added. Generally these are a single new unit test with the code that makes that test pass. The thing that determines what bit gets added next is what needs to get implemented to get the acceptance test error to change to the next step. If you review the commit history you'll see that repeating pattern.

Anyway, let me know how you go and we can get this moving again. Apologies again for the delay, it looks like you've got the lion's share of this worked out and very nicely too. Looking forward to getting it merged in and working with you :)",{},,User,False
