3045,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-24 16:58:18+00:00,8292338,ultrabug/py3status,56311,tobes,,,173989377,255799610,"Revisiting this issue.

If we take the sysdata module as an example.  Currently it can only show one overall threshold, it picks the worst one and colors the output accordingly.

Really we want it to output something like

`sysdata <red>Mem 95%</red> <green>CPU 10%</green>`

Currently we don't have a recommended way to do this. We could do some thing around setting vars in the module say `color_cpu` and `color_mem` and then doing. 

`format = 'sysdata [\?color=mem Mem {mem_used_percent}%] [\?color=cpu CPU {cpu_usage}%]'`

Because of how the get color logic works we need to have the `color_` prefix on the modules attribute.

To me this makes sense as a way to do things, what do others think?

I'm still keen to have a more unified way of doing the thresholds.  I've got some code that moves the threshold processing into Module and Py3 so that we can do the thresholds consistently across modules but first it would be good to decide how we will make the thresholds available to users.

There is also the issue of how we inform the users of the options. @guiniol has come up with this

```
Color conditionals:
    cpu: change color based on the value of cpu_usage
    load: change color based on the value of load1
```

I prefer `Format color options:` but I think adding a new section for this is a good idea.

Another option would be a threshold section

```
Thresholds:
    cpu: percentage cpu usage
    load: percentage load
```
I think that this would have more flexibility as we need to explain what the threshold is based on as some modules may want non-percent values eg temperature.


As far as defining thresholds I'm in favor of

```
module_single_threshold {
    thresholds = [(95, 'bad'), (50, 'good')]
}

module_many_thresholds {
    thresholds = {
             'cpu: [(95, 'bad'), (50, 'good')],
             'mem: [(90, 'bad'), (60, '#f0f')],
    }
}
```

No module currently uses thresholds as a config option a module expecting multiple thresholds could still accept the list and use it for all threshold.  We could then look at deprecating/renaming the old config options, which I think we can do at least initially without users needing to change their configs.",{},,User,False
