3057,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-18 19:47:01+00:00,8292338,ultrabug/py3status,852504,lasers,,,274781084,352537757,"To make the update modules, I worked with pastebin logs in the wild. As of right now, this module is not tested and may need a minor fix somewhere.

The idea about merging everything in one `update` module is not a terrible idea if we can stick with a number of packages. I'm not sure about names and other things.

Things to consider if we truly want to merge absolutely everything...
* My `freebsd` is similar to my `apt_updates`.
* Users likely will want two numbers in `arch_updates`... for `pacman` and `foreign`.
* All update modules I made... contains nearly everything.... which is good for the `formatters`, but not good for this idea.
* `apt_updates` can display individual package types: `new`, `install`, `remove`, `upgrade`, etc.
* Potential issues of documenting everything.
* Placeholders are not always named, but through `.split(':')` or such. This could be an issue of trying to make unified placeholders.
* This approach could be confusing for everyone involved.... Available boolean placeholders for the `formatters` may be found in `apt`, but not `arch`, or was it `xbps` (void)... or `pkg`. We could need a chart for this kind of things too.
* A chart for which we can use `format_update`, `format_install`, etc in.
    `format_update` and `format_install` may be same thing, but is worded differently
between distros... I think `install` mean new package in `apt`, but could be different in `xbps` (void) (regular updating). Not sure.
* An issue of testing this module on distros we need to install... for testing.... if we change something... either small or big... since we would now have one `update` module... so we need to ensure that everything absolutely works for all distros involved.
* I don't want to be a sole contributor fingering all the changes in py3status modules... If you want to try this, go ahead and try.

IIRC @tobes want to do this too. ",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
