3146,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-04 02:34:38+00:00,39159799,JoelBender/bacpypes,10273490,JoelBender,,,285805911,355184224,"I'm not sure why this is happening for you, I can't reproduce it.   When you create an object and give it an object identifier that is an int or a long and not a tuple, it should add the object type as a convenience:
```
>>> from bacpypes.object import AnalogValueObject, DeviceObject
>>> avo = AnalogValueObject(objectIdentifier=12)
>>> avo.debug_contents()
    _app = None
    objectIdentifier = ('analogValue', 12)
>>> do = DeviceObject(objectIdentifier=13)
>>> do.objectIdentifier
('device', 13)
```
LocalDeviceObject is a subclass of DeviceObject and has additional configuration checking and default values and such, but should behave the same way:
```
>>> ldo = LocalDeviceObject(objectIdentifier=12, vendorIdentifier=999)
>>> ldo.debug_contents()
    _app = None
    objectIdentifier = ('device', 12)
    vendorIdentifier = 999
    objectList
        length = 1
        [1] = 12
    maxApduLengthAccepted = 1024
    segmentationSupported = 'segmentedBoth'
    localTime = ()
    localDate = ()
    apduSegmentTimeout = 5000
    apduTimeout = 3000
    numberOfApduRetries = 3
    maxSegmentsAccepted = 16
```
",{},OWNER,User,False
