4029,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-10 08:48:28+00:00,21791607,maxtepkeev/architect,3032449,maxtepkeev,,,99804086,129368485,"Yes, currently architect doesn't provide a way to transfer existing data to partitions automatically, so you have to do this by hand. Let's assume that you have a table called ``logs`` which already have some data inside and you want this table to be partitioned. These are the steps to do that:

1) Rename ``logs`` to ``logs_old``
2) Create new empty ``logs`` table, apply architect decorator and run the partition command to create triggers
3) Move all your data from ``logs_old`` to ``logs`` and it will automatically assign data to needed partitions because triggers are already there",{},,User,False
4030,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-28 11:51:00+00:00,120894,michaeljones/breathe,3614407,Letme,,,103513919,135748483,"You get it right, but I would not agree with your last two paragraphs. I write doxygen comments really strictly, commenting each struct member what it should contain/be used for. Why would I then write that same documentation in .rst again just because I would like a bit more customized output? That is the whole point of breathe - to get doxygen comments inside the rst documentation without having to explain again what certain functions/structs/variables are used for. 

I would simply like to expand the formatting option to tables with a bit more customization to actually displayed values and parameters. Since inline-ing is not an option then argument would be that current representation takes a lot of space, which could be more neatly presented via tables. Also sometimes I would like to see the size of certain struct and tables make a nice representation of that and tables present an easy overview.",{},,User,False
