5254,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-25 21:05:07+00:00,695611,etianen/django-reversion,5481855,ernestoferro,,,209211344,282512340,"Just to clarify, the revision middleware starts the revision before all of
the views (but maybe not of all the other middlewares) start executing. And
it closes the revision in the response after of all of the views have
finished (but again, some other middlewares have execute more things).
Starting a revision also starts an atomic transaction. So in a way, it
behaves almost like ATOMIC_REQUEST=True. And I say almost because there
could be other ""outer"" middlewares executing before and after revision.

In summary, there are not the same thing. They just happen to have almost
the same outcome. To the point where setting atomic transaction to true
will make no difference if the revisions middleware is in use.

I hope this clarifies the situation.

On Sat, Feb 25, 2017, 3:51 PM Maksim Iakovlev, <notifications@github.com>
wrote:

> Can RevisionMiddleware take into consideration non_atomic_requests? Maybe
> we already have enough ways to disable transactions (decorator and
> AUTO_REQUESTS=False)?
>
