6217,IssueCommentEvent,2015-04-07 16:52:06+00:00,3583594,lambdalisue/django-permission,289531,stevelacey,,,66850590,90643620,"I appreciate the time you've taken here thanks.

I am pretty sure I've wrapped my head around it, I was just leaving the nonsensical comments as a way of seeing the thought process I went through to get to this point.

# Affirmative approach

I think it's worth outlining how your library takes the **affirmative** approach, even if other Django permissions tend to do it the same way, just to make it clear – personally, I am mapping your approach to my Symfony2 understanding described at http://symfony.com/doc/current/components/security/authorization.html#access-decision-manager

> affirmative (default)
> grant access as soon as any voter returns an affirmative response;

One for the docs?

--

So, based on:

> Multiple permission logics can be specified to a single model, even multiple models.

All custom logics I attach to a model will be ran, and as long as at least one returns `True`, the user is allowed the permission, otherwise they are not, and the order in which they're ran should be irrelevant. Yes?

# Custom logic vs db values

> No, it appears, if a custom logic is set for a model then it is always ran and the db described permissions joint to the user/group are ignored?

What I was asking here is whether the custom logic negates any values in the `user_permissions` table – but based on what you've described ""prefer `True`"", that as long as either a custom logic returns `True`, or a user is bound to a permission via `user_group_permissions` or `user_permissions`, that as long as one of them is `True`, they'll be granted that permission?",{},,User,False
