6681,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-31 17:56:38+00:00,79584587,yahoo/TensorFlowOnSpark,3676078,leewyang,16574,yahoo,266732496,340848690,"I think you need to set the GPU ""compute mode"" to ""exclusive process"", since it looks like you're able to schedule two processes onto the same GPU.  We assume this in our code (and in our environment), since A) it's a simpler model to reason about, and B) you often write TF code to maximize GPU throughput (e.g. memory, batch_size, etc), which can be a problem if there are other processes on the same GPU.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
6686,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-22 22:38:47+00:00,79584587,yahoo/TensorFlowOnSpark,3676078,leewyang,16574,yahoo,289520773,359594956,"> I have one more question.
> I set spark_worker_instances=4 but, one is ps , others are workers(0,1,2).
> Why there isn't 4th worker?

Unfortunately `spark_worker_instances` is a bit confusing here.  It's essentially the number of Spark executors, i.e. `num_executors`.  And in TFoS, since we stand up the entire TF cluster on the executors, then `num_workers + num_ps == num_executors`.

And, if you're using Standalone mode with HDFS, you will likely still need to set the path to LIB_HDFS, per the [YARN Instructions](https://github.com/yahoo/TensorFlowOnSpark/wiki/GetStarted_YARN#convert-the-mnist-zip-files-into-hdfs-files)",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
