7967,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-01 12:29:54+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,8616788,commutecat,327752,boto,148877367,222977556,"@hobofan  : virtualenv are recommended, even for cloud. One issue of python package is access withoout `sudo`, virtualenv allow you to do that.  Also AWS resources has its own catch. 

For aws credentials , the common mistake made for multiple profile is omitting the ""profile"" in the config 
```
#~/.aws/credential
[default] 
aws_access_key_id= ....
aws_secret_access_key=....

[superapp]
aws_access_key_id= ....
aws_secret_access_key=....

# The catch, 
#~/.aws/config
[default]
region = .....

# so the alternate profile, in the config, you must prefix it with profile , follow by space, then profile name
[profile superapp]
region = .....
```
",{},,User,False
7968,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-28 16:28:38+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,4605355,kyleknap,327752,boto,96817067,125671463,"I am not able to reproduce this:
```py
In [1]: from boto3.session import Session

In [2]: session = Session(region_name='us-west-2')

In [3]: client = session.resource('iam')

In [4]: user = client.User('foo')

In [5]: user.create()
Out[5]: iam.User(name='foo')
```

However based on your debug logs, I see what your issue is. You are trying to connect to http://iam.amazonaws.com/. However, IAM endpoint can only being connected through https: http://docs.aws.amazon.com/general/latest/gr/rande.html#iam_region

Are you setting an ``endpoint_url`` somewhere in your code to force the endpoint to use http?",{},,User,False
