8024,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-04 05:08:37+00:00,6670942,boto/botocore,190930,mtdowling,327752,boto,127803257,179643297,"We chatted about this in the office the other day, we all agreed that it's fine to stay a string, and obfuscating the string would be fine as well. The most apparent use case of providing an input token to a paginator is to resume pagination from a previously created paginator. The token is, and should be, opaque; however, customers could still provide the other API parameters that could influence pagination.

Some of the things we talked about that might be a good idea are to use JSON instead of relying on Python's AST parser, and update the string to always be a hash of values instead of a list (this would match how Ruby and PHP are implemented).

The backwards compatibility concern is a good point. I think though that even if we continue to use a string, the level of change of the format in this PR would still break users who are using a token that was previously persisted. Like you said though, I highly doubt anyone has done this.",{},,User,False
8028,IssueCommentEvent,2016-04-29 18:00:20+00:00,6670942,boto/botocore,2643092,JordonPhillips,327752,boto,151929836,215831192,"We can, but this would allow us to take advantage of the built in automatic flush in python 3. It also saves us a line of code, not that that's a huge deal.",{},,User,False
8029,IssueCommentEvent,2015-03-16 20:43:56+00:00,6670942,boto/botocore,106826,danielgtaylor,327752,boto,60563334,81927131,@jamesls @kyleknap please take another look.,{},,User,False
8030,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-29 01:28:59+00:00,6670942,boto/botocore,5866405,DenverJ,327752,boto,113741754,152047396,"Yep, I have done exactly that and abstracted it away. It works great and for our home-grown apps it's not a problem. But as mentioned, the goal for this is to be able to use open source projects etc that expect to find credentials in the usual places. With the new shared credentials location it also allows us to use one way to provide credentials for apps written in languages other than python. 

Reading from the credentials file every time was the simplest solution but below are some other suggestions that still employ caching.
* Write expiration time to credentials file and use that to auto-refresh
* Refresh credentials every 60 seconds.
* Refresh credentials as part of request retry

I'm happy to raise a PR if we can find an approach that would be acceptable.",{},,User,False
