8752,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-21 03:59:36+00:00,2504175,nodeca/js-yaml,43677,js-choi,723678,nodeca,208509806,281239186,"To be technical, the YAML specification does not require that non-tagged mapping nodes (i.e., those with the implicit `?` non-specific tag) have the same type as mapping nodes tagged with `!!map` (`tag:yaml.org,2002:map`) or even the `!` non-specific tag. (For more on non-specific tags, see also [§ 3.3.2 Resolved Tags, first paragraph](http://www.yaml.org/spec/1.2/spec.html#tag/non-specific/) and [§ 6.9.1 Node Tags, Non-Specific Tags](http://www.yaml.org/spec/1.2/spec.html#id2784064).) Instead, non-tagged mapping nodes’ types are determined by the application schema’s tag resolution.

This provides easy, standard ways to distinguish objects from maps. For instance, the Mozilla Developer Network gives the following example for ES Maps:

    var myMap = new Map();

    var keyString = 'a string',
        keyObj = {},
        keyFunc = function() {};

    // setting the values
    myMap.set(keyString, ""value associated with 'a string'"");
    myMap.set(keyObj, 'value associated with keyObj');
    myMap.set(keyFunc, 'value associated with keyFunc');

…which requires distinguishing between `Map`s and generic objects.

Under an opt-in schema, that `Map` might be written as the following:

    ! a string: value associated with 'a string'
      {}: value associated with keyObj
      !!js/function 'function() {}': value associated with keyFunc

…whose non-specific tags would then resolve to:

    !map
      !str a string: value associated with 'a string'
      !!js/object {}: value associated with keyObj
      !!js/function 'function() {}': value associated with keyFunc

In this schema, `?`-tagged YAML mappings (i.e., non-tagged mappings) resolve into ES Maps. A user might opt into this schema the usual way:

    const YAML = require('js-yaml');
    YAML.load(`...`, { schema: YAML.ES_CORE_SCHEMA });

However, the *default* schema (`DEFAULT_SAFE_SCHEMA`) would remain the same for backwards compatibility; no existing users’ code would be affected as far as I could tell.

In any case, if there is little demand for this, then that is fine. I’m figuring out a solution myself. Thanks again for the response. I'll close this issue for now.",{},,User,False
