9987,IssueCommentEvent,2017-07-30 20:16:19+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,623887,rmjarvis,1462196,GalSim-developers,246604263,318926630,"I'm on 10.10 myself, so might not have a huge amount of helpful advice here.  But that said, I'll try.

>  I looked up at the top and it said it found FFTW, but it didn't say where. I don't understand why 10.5 would even be relevant, since I was on OSX 10.9 before this.

I think this is probably important.  You likely need to reinstall fftw.  As for why 10.5 rather than 10.9, my guess is that the ABI compatibility didn't change between 10.5 and 10.9, so they probably just called it 10.5 for all in between.  Then sometime between 10.9 and 10.12, they probably changed something that made it non-ABI-compatible.  In any case, probably best to delete any libfftw.a files that are on your system from the old OS and reinstall new ones.

> clang: error: linker command failed with exit code 1 (use -v to see invocation)

Sounds like something with the Boost linking.  Did you remove the old version of boos from your system?  There's no point keeping it around, so if you didn't, probably a good idea.  Otherwise it's possible that the linker isn't finding the right boost library to link to.

You can also have it report the libraries being linked by running the linking command yourself with verbose output.
```
clang++ -v -Wl,--verbose -o galsim/_galsim.so -bundle ...
```
Then you can check that it's using the right versions of boost, fftw, and tmv.",{},,User,False
9993,IssueCommentEvent,2016-05-02 18:11:50+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,623887,rmjarvis,1462196,GalSim-developers,116097672,216314900,">  I suspect that is a level of detail that is really only required for people who are trying to simulate an actual LSST pointing, as opposed to just simulating a possible LSST image.

I think that's right.  Nowhere else in GalSim do we try to get any of these kinds of details right.  We pretty much assume that there is some RA, Dec system that you are using and the WCS just translates between that and chip coords.  We don't do precession or distinguish FK5 from ICRS, etc.

Furthermore, most of what we care about is the complexity of the WCS relative to the center of the field of view.  Not getting the overall pointing perfectly oriented.  So I'd suggest just ignoring these details and start at whatever the most convenient RA/Dec system is for constructing the WCS.",{},,User,False
