10443,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-09 09:51:35+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,3407345,CyberDem0n,1564818,zalando,311666174,395956132,"Unfortunately there are too many ambiguities in the second approach.
It is not possible to know from the slot name whether it was created by Patroni or not.
Just think about a situation when Patroni was restarted and at the same time, one of the members expires from DCS. Upon start, Patroni will see that there is a slot, but no member in DCS. Should it remove this slot? I think yes, it should.

Patroni creates/removes replication slots only if the list of members changes and it never removes active slots.
@alago197 I think that the current behaviour is more or less fine for you. ",{},MEMBER,User,False
10446,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-12 23:21:36+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,115146,jberkus,1564818,zalando,262926907,336307739,"**Race Conditions During Operation**

Because Etcd TTLs are client-based, we can have an issue of inconsistency between nodes if system clocks on the nodes are sufficiently different.  For example, if the TTL for the master lock is seen as expired by a replica and non-expired by the current master.  

However, it is unclear on what specific harm this would cause other than an unnecessary failover.  Discuss.

",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
