10903,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-03 23:02:22+00:00,10340514,savoirfairelinux/num2words,17234418,HawkingJan,2735545,savoirfairelinux,150717971,237401792,"To get ""Ein EURO Komma Dreiundzwanzig"" one would have to split up the floating number and then use num2words separately on 1 (which would give ""eins"" instead of ""ein"", see my comment) and on 23 which would give correct ""Dreiundzwanzig"". The variant ""Eins Dreiundzwanzig"" might be used in spoken language (e.g. if you pay at the supermarket) but I would consider this quite informal.

Regarding your comment about the prefix ""Ein"" before hundert and tausend, I think the current variant is a correct variant (but yours is also OK). See for example the Duden 
http://www.duden.de/rechtschreibung/tausend
which writhes  ""[ein]tausend[und]achtzig"" or here 
https://deutsch.lingolia.com/de/wortschatz/zahlen-datum-uhrzeit/kardinalzahlen
where they explicitly state ""Am Wortanfang können wir die Zahlen einhundert/eintausend zu hundert/tausend kürzen."" On this website they also mention that ""Ein(s)"" is special.

