11458,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-09 02:23:06+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,294674234,364315510,"Oh! Here's an entirely different suggestion (take it or leave it, but I think it's good!): what if you declared dependencies on binary tools by declaring a dependency on a scoped instance of `""BinarySubsystem""` (names, whatever):

```
def subsystem_dependencies(..):
  return super(..) + BinarySubsystem.scoped(""protoc"")
```

...and then added a way to get all registered instances of a particular Subsystem? This has the added benefit of being much, much more declarative. And I love Subsystems (prefer composition over inheritance, etc!)",{},OWNER,User,False
11462,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-01 18:49:01+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,327858152,393975853,"> But publishing each checker separately seems like a hassle

Yea. Do we think that it would be possible to resolve pexes for the target platform at runtime with the sources for the checkers as input? This would be similar to what we do for pytest. cc @jsirois 

> and invoking each one separately seems like a potential performance hit.

I'm less concerned about the performance, because with remoting this will mean that we can run the checks in parallel automatically",{},MEMBER,User,False
