12380,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-30 20:15:15+00:00,2113510,crossbario/autobahn-python,145599,meejah,5656948,crossbario,192345036,263982586,"Yeah, it's kind of a fine line/point. Personally, I think ""being explicit"" is nice -- *especially* if we fix the docs so it doesn't take digging to figure that out.  BUT on the other hand if you already leaped through enough fire-y hoops to make a client-side certificate work, ...

That said, I'm trying to imagine a case where you'd want to do TLS client-auth on the transport, but do some *other* thing to authenticate the realm at the WAMP level. If there's *never* such a case, then maybe ""non-explict, slightly magic"" is fine...

I do have some PoC stuff in the works to make authentication way better overall -- so you don't have to muck around with `join()` or overriding `onChallenge` at all (except for ""odd"" cases).",{},,User,False
