12471,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-06 08:54:47+00:00,23788348,swisscom/cleanerversion,1587013,maennel,5754111,swisscom,202492011,277619155,"@mikeengland while adding tests for MySQL/MariaDB, I stumbled upon an issue regarding timestamp precision with earlier versions of MySQL/MariaDB. So, please make sure you have the maximum precision (which is ""6"" positions after the comma) enabled for all DateTime fields on all Versionable models (`version_birth_date`, `version_start_date`, and `version_end_date`). 
Otherwise, you may run into issues (for example quite a number of tests does not pass with ""0"" precision, i.e. all timestamps rounded to the next full second).
See this link for more info: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.8/ref/databases/#fractional-seconds-support-for-time-and-datetime-fields",{},,User,False
12486,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-30 16:39:16+00:00,14318232,soft-matter/pims,2279598,danielballan,5857177,soft-matter,96084997,126396786,"I'm convinced. To be sure, I made two demo tiff stacks, color and grayscale variants of the words ""This Side Up."" I read it with the three tiff readers using current master and this PR.

* [Current Behavior](http://nbviewer.ipython.org/gist/danielballan/a35bee4fa06dcb09b3b0)
* [New Behavior Proposed in this PR](http://nbviewer.ipython.org/gist/danielballan/32095e6f329efc002d26)

With @lschr's changes, all readers show the image in the correct orientation. They should never have been rotated in the first place. I think I put that in while wrestling with a weird format in my early days of learning Python. Later, @tacaswell dutifully propagated my code, and here we are. Sorry that it caused headaches.

This change also makes `v[0].shape` and `v.frame_shape` internally consistent (which we should cover with unit tests!) and shows the image in the correct orientation.

As a side note, these notebooks show that our PIL reader can't read color images. @tacaswell or I will fix that in a separate PR.

This may break user code, but it's the right thing thing to do.",{},,User,False
12487,IssueCommentEvent,2018-04-10 19:57:16+00:00,4744355,soft-matter/trackpy,2985325,nkeim,5857177,soft-matter,312199841,380227204,"Let's not forget about this PR entirely! It might be advisable under a general housecleaning for v0.5.

@apiszcz As far as I know, `enable_numba()` was *never* required; numba is always enabled by default if it is available. The purpose of `disable_numba()` and `enable_numba()` was to allow testing of the un-compiled functions. This was back when numba was still exotic and sometimes temperamental.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
12488,IssueCommentEvent,2015-05-01 16:39:17+00:00,4744355,soft-matter/trackpy,2985325,nkeim,5857177,soft-matter,71694307,98174360,"I forgot about R_g (""size""). It seems like the bandpassed image would be better for that, since otherwise, noise will always inflate R_g. But that means people like me who do weird nonlinear preprocessing would still need to do a second pass with `refine()` to get more accurate R_g.

The most generally correct way to compute R_g would be from the raw image, with noise removed *only*.",{},,User,False
