12879,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-09 08:33:44+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,810663,pelson,6392739,conda,54483608,146796734,"> What other ""alternative paradigms"" are you thinking about?

Conda already works pretty well outside of the root environment (provided you install it manually, or create an environment with a leading underscore). The biggest problem which is encountered when doing this is that the ```pkgs``` and ```envs``` directories are assumed to be put in the installed conda's prefix - if that assumption were broken, and the directories were actually put a level below the installed conda's prefix, you end up with a structure:

```
${CONDA_INSTALL_LOCATION}/
                           pkgs/
                           envs/
                                conda_root/
                                           bin/conda
                                conda_py2k_root/
                                           bin/conda
                                my_py2_env/
                                           bin/python
                                my_py3_env/
                                           bin/python
                           bin/
                               conda -> (symlink to) ../envs/conda_root/bin/conda
                               activate -> (symlink to) ../envs/conda_root/bin/activate
                               deactivate -> (symlink to) ../envs/conda_root/bin/deactivate
```

There are some details to thrash out about how conda finds its subcommands (e.g. ``conda-build``) but I think pulling that from the conda executable's path (i.e. not the symlink's path) is perfectly attainable. This approach has the advantage of never needing to remove ``${CONDA_INSTALL_LOCATION}/bin`` from the PATH within the activate script, as it is a very lightweight directory containing the 3 key conda top level executables. The other advantage is that symlinks would not be necessary within each environment that point to the ""root"" conda - this also makes it possible to install a different conda into another environment, activate that environment, and be able to use that version of conda (essentially, conda is no longer special)
",{},,User,False
