13128,IssueCommentEvent,2017-07-13 04:23:23+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,1329240,troydai,6844498,Azure,242499990,314966892,"The root cause is a performance optimization [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-cli/blob/master/src/command_modules/azure-cli-storage/azure/cli/command_modules/storage/util.py#L28). When the pattern doesn't contain a wildcard, we use it as blob name directly to fetch the source so as to save the listing cost. Hence the inconsistency. This can be fixed.

However, I'd like to point out one thing. Blob container is not considered as a hierarchy of directories, which is file share. The blobs' names may look like a path, but it doesn't indicate a tree topology. In blob container, you cannot create an empty directory and you can move content from one directory to another. To mock a file system, you should consider Azure File Share.

And in your case, if `foo` is indeed representing a directory, then this command `az storage blob copy start-batch ... --pattern ""foo""` shouldn't be necessary. Because there isn't a `foo` blob. When copy `foo/bar` blob to the destination container will essentially be established the `foo` because it is a segment contained in `foo/bar` name string. Now, because blob container is not a file system. Then `foo` can exist as a blob. However, then in this case, `foo*` matches `foo1` is a perfectly correct match.

I'll add this to sprint 19 for now.",{},,User,False
