13179,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-19 20:11:08+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,12519400,hectoralicea,6844498,Azure,333726929,398529214,"Got it to work by adding a ```az network lb frontend-ip update```  command following the ```az network lb frontend-ip create``` .  So my code looks like this:

```
az network lb frontend-ip create --lb-name ${lb_name} --name ${frontend_ip_2} --resource-group ${RG} --private-ip-address ${webintranet_lb_ip} --subnet ${subnetid}
az network lb frontend-ip update --lb-name ${lb_name} --name ${frontend_ip_2} --resource-group ${RG} --private-ip-address ${webintranet_lb_ip} --set privateIpAllocationMethod=Static ; sleep 3

```
in cases where its the second frontend-ip being created I had to add the update command to ensure that the private ip sticks and that the privateIpAllocationMethod sets to Static.  Running debug before the update command is set, the status of the private-ip-address is that its assigned to the lowest IP available in the subnet, and the privateIpAllocationMethod=Dynamic.  After the update command, the IP changes to what I wanted it to be set to in the first command and the privateIpAllocationMethod=Static",{},NONE,User,False
13181,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-21 01:34:32+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,16448634,derekbekoe,6844498,Azure,202211269,274222464,"There was a change in import logic in Python 3.4.1 -https://docs.python.org/3/whatsnew/3.4.html#whatsnew-pep-451.

Also, `importlib.find_loader()` was introduced (and then later deprecated) which produces a similar error to above - https://docs.python.org/3/library/importlib.html#importlib.find_loader.

```
>>> importlib.find_loader('pip')
<_frozen_importlib.SourceFileLoader object at 0x7f8c0a1f1a90>
>>> importlib.find_loader('azure')
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.4/importlib/__init__.py"", line 70, in find_loader
    raise ValueError('{}.__loader__ is None'.format(name))
ValueError: azure.__loader__ is None
>>> importlib.find_loader('azure.cli')
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.4/importlib/__init__.py"", line 70, in find_loader
    raise ValueError('{}.__loader__ is None'.format(name))
ValueError: azure.cli.__loader__ is None
```

Related:
http://bugs.python.org/issue17099

3.4.1 was released in 2014.
""A newer bugfix release, 3.4.3, is currently available. Its use is recommended.""
https://www.python.org/download/releases/3.4.1/

Current recommendation is to upgrade Python version.",{},,User,False
