13715,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-25 09:32:31+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,705404,mgeier,7388996,jupyter,151104892,228526334,"Inserting the additional space only after headings feels like a hack, and it would still produce too little space after equations, tables, images, ...

In the meantime I found out why the rules mentioned above (https://github.com/jupyter/notebook/issues/1392#issuecomment-215022995) don't work:

```css
* + ul { margin-top: 1em; }
* + ol { margin-top: 1em; }
```

They were simply overruled by:

```css
ol:not(.list-inline) {margin: 0em 2em; padding-left: 0px;}
```

I removed this bug in #1568, which I think is a slight improvement, but it's still broken.
Especially nested lists still look awkward. You can try something like this:

```markdown
* first item
  * first subitem
  * second subitem
  
  paragraph after second subitem
* second item

  paragraph inside second item
* third item
```

The real problem, however, isn't only list spacing. The spacing of `<p>` and many other elements just doesn't work well together.
Sadly, I don't know enough CSS-fu to produce a solution for the whole problem, I hope somebody else does that!",{},,User,False
