13949,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-08 17:13:58+00:00,27082457,HIPS/autograd,1458824,mattjj,7935606,HIPS,169703697,238304817,"We also have the reparameterization trick in [some](https://github.com/HIPS/autograd/blob/master/examples/black_box_svi.py) [examples](https://github.com/HIPS/autograd/blob/master/examples/bayesian_neural_net.py), thanks to @duvenaud. I think this method is essentially what the Schulman et al. paper calls the pathwise derivative (PD) (also discussed in Section 7.2 of the REINFORCE paper, and elsewhere). You can also write the score function (SF) estimator easily with autograd, though I don't think we have any in our examples directory.

So you can already use autograd to implement these methods, and we'd like to add more examples. However, you could imagine a different library which takes some abstract representation of an objective function expressed as the expectation of a random variable and automatically rewrites it into one of these Monte Carlo estimates (to which autodiff can be applied). That's the kind of thing that libraries like Edward might do, and those libraries sit on top of autodiff libraries, but it's outside the scope of autograd itself (we don't have abstractions for random variables, etc.). Hopefully using autograd makes these kinds of tools as easy to write as possible!

Does that make sense? Did I get anything wrong? ",{},,User,False
