14304,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-19 11:54:57+00:00,18891741,pytest-dev/pytest-cov,5114350,TheFriendlyCoder,8897583,pytest-dev,266492014,337884899,"Ok - so I think I have this mostly working. I've added a call to `coverage run` inside my docker container, and I've confirmed the tool correctly generates a .coverage file for the source files running inside the container. Then I've shared this file with my host PC and I've confirmed that `coverage combine` successfully merges the .coverage file generated from within the container with the .coverage file generated by pytest-cov on my host....

However, `coverage report` throws some errors and produces a partial report. It seems that when `coverage combine` runs it uses absolute paths for the .py files that were instrumented during the metric gathering process... and since the paths to my library packages are different inside the Docker container than they are on my host, it gets confused. It seems combine isn't smart enough to map metrics from, say `/opt/lib/python3.4/site-packages/mylib/__init__.py` with the metrics for `$PWD/mylib/__init__.py`.

Do you have any recommendataions on how to work around this problem? One thing I had in mind was to hack the .coverage file generated inside my container to rewrite the paths from the container to their respective locations on my host before running `coverage combine`, but I'm hoping there will be a more robust and less hack-ish way of doing this.",{},NONE,User,False
