14533,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-16 17:15:52+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,1581662,jdkasten,9289019,letsencrypt,110879110,157104089,"@jsha  Yes, the restart was implemented and //todo added... just to get
around the race condition temporarily.  I think the only viable solution is
to poll the server checking for the changes, it just requires a bit more
code.

IIRC, the reload timings (configuration changes) had a very high variance.

That being said, all webservers can reuse the same code to test for the
challenges.  (It can be added to the plugins directory within letsencrypt)

On Mon, Nov 16, 2015 at 8:56 AM, Jacob Hoffman-Andrews <
notifications@github.com> wrote:

> Note: there is almost certainly going to be a race condition on reload for
> both Nginx and Apache: the servers will take a non-zero amount of time to
> process the signal, parse the new config, and start serving with it. I did
> run into this race condition pretty reliably when working on the Nginx
> code. That's why I recommend adding an explicit loop check to wait until
> the new config is actually serving before proceeding with processing.
>
> —
> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub
> <https://github.com/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/issues/954#issuecomment-157096333>
> .
>
",{},,User,False
