14614,IssueCommentEvent,2016-05-05 14:01:06+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,541623,aptalca,9289019,letsencrypt,149061443,217162393,"I'd like to echo iangelov's request. I created a docker container that has nginx with letsencrypt renewal built-in. Most of the users are running this container on NAS systems, where port 80 is reserved for the NAS gui, and some others have their port 80 blocked either on the router or by their ISP. There are many reasons for not being able to use port 80 on a home web server.

The standalone plugin has the tls-sni-01 option that works beautifully for verification through port 443. But the webroot method does not currently have such an option (only port 80).

I am happy to use the standalone plugin to generate the certs the first time. After that, I would like to be able to use the webroot plugin to renew them so that I don't have to take the existing webserver offline during renewals.

Also, the newly added renew parameter in the auto script doesn't have the ability to temporarily take down the other webserver if a renewal is needed. So if you set it to run with renew every night, you have to take the webserver offline every night in case the auto script decides to renew. The other option is to not use the renew parameter, and instead implement a different algorithm that tries and figures out whether the certs need to be renewed, and then force a renewal with the auto script (why reinvent the wheel when the auto script already has that algorithm built-in)",{},,User,False
14615,IssueCommentEvent,2016-03-18 00:33:57+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,6504915,bmw,9289019,letsencrypt,140300417,198144598,"This looks good! My only suggestion is that perhaps `renew()` should be moved into `main.py`.

This allows us to stop hacking around cyclic import problems and allows `main` and all subcommands to exist in `main.py`.

`renew.py` can continue to contain functions that provide much of the renewal functionality (in actuality, this code is spread throughout the project in places such as `storage.py`). `renew()` could be refactored into additional functions that exist in `renew.py`. This refactoring could be a bit tricky, however.

Alternatively, `renew()` could stay as is and just call relevant functions from `renew.py` which is already imported and used in `main.py`.",{},,User,False
