15084,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-28 22:40:20+00:00,95862535,apple/coremltools,7546478,aseemw,10639145,apple,326809946,392612778,"Thank you for using coremltools and reporting the issue!

Looking at the error it seems that the converter is trying to find out the values for the input image's height, width and channel and failing in that. 

I think I know why. Have you tried looking at the keras model and checking that its input shape is properly defined? 

```
from keras.models import load_model
model = load_model('model_data/yolo.h5')
print(model.input_shape)
```

I believe the height/width are not defined in the Keras model (it might be None). CoreML needs to know the exact values for Height/Width. 
The solution would be to edit the script that is producing the Keras model. This might be the [location](https://github.com/qqwweee/keras-yolo3/blob/68988ccbe8b0cb6832deb9e227e158c9be977cdb/convert.py#L88). 

I'll keep this issue open. CoreML tools should have better error message for a situation like this. 

",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
15086,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-15 09:38:04+00:00,86575060,linnarsson-lab/loompy,16916678,falexwolf,10656411,linnarsson-lab,273998324,344537740,"Thank you, Sten! This discussion is exactly what we need, I think.

**Orientation**: I'd vote for rows to be cells and columns to be genes, as in the modern classics of Statistics [Hastie et al. (2009)](https://web.stanford.edu/~hastie/ElemStatLearn/) and Machine Learning [Murphy (2012)](https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/machine-learning-0), in dataframes both in R and Python and the established machine learning and statistics packages in Python ([statsmodels](http://www.statsmodels.org/stable/index.html), [scikit-learn](http://scikit-learn.org/)). But I acknowledge that for genomic data, the tradition is the opposite and I'm happy to conform with that, if most of you think it this is the better choice. 

**Other annotation/attributes**: The naming conventions are fine! But I'd suggest that one also allows arbitrary multi-dimensional annotation. The PCA representation of data can easily have 50 dimensions. It is not very intuititve to label all of these by `X`, `Y`, ... or `X_pca1`, `X_pca2`, .... Same for the PCs themselves (`PC1`, `PC2`, etc.), which are gene attributes. See what I've written below on how we solve this within AnnData.

**Graphs**: `KNN` implies that there is a [fixed degree k](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nearest_neighbor_graph) per node and one might go beyond that in the future (btw: What is the `MKNN` graph?). We might also have graphs whose weights correspond to distances and graphs whose weights correspond to probabilities and similar issues. But this could be distinguished simply by providing a suffix, e.g. `KNN_distances`. What about 'cell_graph', 'CellGraph', 'SingleCellGraph' or 'neighborhood_graph'?

I agree that the loom file format should stay as general as possible. For my taste, even more general. It would be nice if loom can at least cope with what [AnnData](https://scanpy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/scanpy.api.AnnData.html) can store, which is otherwise very similar to loom: We allow arbitrary structured and unstructured annotation/metadata/attributes, and only distinguish inherently one-dimensional (numerical or categorical annotation), multi-dimensional (something like the PCA representation of data 'X_pca', mentioned above) and unstructured annotation. For instance, graphs (e.g., single-cell graph: sparse matrix whose node attributes are cell attributes) do not fit into the data/annotation/attributes [block scheme](https://scanpy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/basic_usage.html#anndata-objects) and hdf5 does not support sparse matrices. Hence graphs appear as ""unstructured annotation"" within AnnData - even though they are sliced  (subsampling, indexing, etc.). Also, we make use of the unstructured annotation for categorical data types, for non-single-cell graphs, etc.. But this is now turning into the specifics of how Scanpy/AnnData objects can be represented as loom files: https://github.com/linnarsson-lab/loompy/issues/1#issuecomment-344525924 as opposed to the [inherent hdf5-format of AnnData](https://scanpy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/scanpy.api.write.html).

I guess similar issues arise for Seurat objects,  Pagoda objects and others. I'd be interested in reading about these issues so that we can all find good best practices.

Cheers,
  Alex
 ",{},NONE,User,False
