15818,IssueCommentEvent,2016-01-06 19:46:59+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,2956460,squilter,12973369,dronekit,125102970,169438118,"All works on my computer.  Not sure why the test is failing.  Maybe it's because of the version that sitl is running?  If sitl is running an older version, then it would send lots of 0's in the `AUTOPILOT_VERSION` message, which would lead to this failing.",{},,User,False
15820,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-08 22:35:34+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,9061756,yoshiioko,12973369,dronekit,260612829,356118668,"Hi asiyo,

I was having the same issue as you when trying to run a program to connect to my device (Intel Aero drone). FYI, I ran the program from within the Aero drone itself. Had to make these changes:

1. Updated the main.conf file for the mavlink-router with an additional UDP endpoint by adding these lines:
`[UdpEndpoint dronekit]`
`Mode = Normal`
`Address = 127.0.0.1`
`Port = 11000`

2. Restarted mavlink-router service:
`systemctl restart mavlink-router`

3. Changed connect() to just do this:
`vehicle = connect('127.0.0.1:11000')`

I am not an expert! But I can now get some vehicle state data from the system.

",{},NONE,User,False
15823,IssueCommentEvent,2018-04-07 16:06:29+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,5058646,pietrodn,12973369,dronekit,310335635,379480219,http://python.dronekit.io/contributing/contributions_documentation.html,{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
15825,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-08 09:44:20+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,5368500,hamishwillee,12973369,dronekit,131838689,181278197,"@makkaa94 What you need to do is read the docs - that explains what dronekit-python will do for you and what dronekit-sitl will do for you: http://python.dronekit.io/ There are lots of examples. One to start with is in the [quickstart here](http://python.dronekit.io/guide/quick_start.html#basic-hello-drone) - this actually launches SITL for you from the script.

So Dronekit-Sitl is just an easy way of setting up SITL. It installs native binaries for your OS and runs them. This means that you don't need to build the source, or set up cygwin or anything like that. You have a version of SITL running on your machine, and you can connect to it on tcp:127.0.0.1:5760 from DroneKit. See http://python.dronekit.io/develop/sitl_setup.html

> So after installing the dronekit-python packages, onto the host machine, and editing a code on the host machine, 'import dronekit' should give me access to a new set of commands to control the drone with?allowing me to construct a longer script, and being able to press play once and the drone will follow the script?

After you install dronekit python you can call methods from the dronekit API. You can call `import dronekit` but it is more common to just import the bits you need (the minimal version is as below)

```
from dronekit import connect, 
```
You can construct long scripts or short scripts - check out the examples.
I don't know what you mean by ""press play"". You need to read the docs, because they really do give you step by step guidance. I am assuming you already have some idea of Python 2 programming.

Hope that helps!

",{},,User,False
