16071,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-08 19:58:15+00:00,30212825,Amber-MD/pytraj,10144183,drroe,13525542,Amber-MD,321174504,387523690,"What is the size of `my_traj.nc`? The `createcrd` command is saving the trajectory to memory, and since you're not doing any stripping of coordinates the entire thing has to fit in memory. If it's a large trajectory (i.e. bigger than your available memory) you have to either 1) strip it down so it fits (so in your case strip all hydrogens - if there are waters you probably want to strip those as well) or 2) keep the trajectory on-disk and run in two passes. The thing to keep in mind with 2) is that you need to make sure the input trajectory is processed the same way when projecting the coordinates as when generating the covariance matrix, e.g.
```
# Step one. Generate average structure.
# RMS-Fit to first frame to remove global translation/rotation.
parm myparm.parm7
trajin mytraj.nc
rms first !@H=
average crdset AVG
run
# Step two. RMS-Fit to average structure. Calculate covariance matrix.
rms ref AVG !@H=
matrix covar name MyMatrix !@H=
run
# Step three. Diagonalize matrix.
runanalysis diagmatrix MyMatrix vecs 2 name MyEvecs
# Step four. Project saved fit coordinates along eigenvectors 1 and 2
# Note that we must RMS-fit the input trajectory the same as when
# generating the covariance matrix.
rms ref AVG !@H=
projection evecs MyEvecs !@H= out project.dat beg 1 end 2
run
```",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
