4) parse_eigen is True by default in the vasprun.xml
I did a quick set of tests and I don't see any decrease in speed for Vasprun + BSVasprun( parse_projected_eigen=True) vs. Vasprun( parse_projected_eigen=True)
It's really only because I need some of the logic from Vasprun to decide if projections should be parsed. 
5) We don't get back the linemode style when the Kpoints object is made from a Kpoints file, so I'm just checking for the existence of explicit kpoints. There might be a better way to do this. ",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
16219,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-04 17:17:40+00:00,43023379,hackingmaterials/atomate,986759,computron,14116185,hackingmaterials,250717820,386668290,@richardtran415 any update on this?,{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
16223,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-27 20:21:25+00:00,43091756,hackingmaterials/matminer,986759,computron,14116185,hackingmaterials,300525785,369013093,"So why don't people just use the sklearn version? I see no reason to reimplement it yourself within a single estimator (this makes no sense at all, since other estimators can't easily call it) or even putting it in matminer utils (the same function already exists in sklearn, which is a requirement of matminer!)

Honestly I'd just put a simple ""if not <parameter exists>, throw error"". Or if you don't want to do that, call the sklearn function",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
16225,IssueCommentEvent,2017-07-10 23:25:33+00:00,43091756,hackingmaterials/matminer,8696276,matk86,14116185,hackingmaterials,241412744,314277822,"1. yes, it should be done.

2. The CompositionFeaturizer in compostion.py subclasses AbstractFeaturizer and all composition related featurizers in compostion.py inherits from CompositionFeaturizer not AbstractFeaturizer. AbstractFeaturizer is something that all featurizers(composition or structure or something else in the future) should inherit. I agree, all the composition related featurizers should follow the pattern set in compositions.py. For structures, the signature for 'featurize' will be different(or at least that how it seems like). So for the time being i have left out the implementation for featurizers in the strucure.py module.

3. The way it is implemented now ensures that the property values can be obtained from either data source using a common api and in the composition featurizers the default source is set to be magpie if the user doesn't explicitly specify the source or don't really care about where the data is from. This model ensures that in the future if someone decides to use a different data source that is not already in matminer they could just add their own data source class in data.py module and the only thing they have to ensure is that their implementation subclasses the AbstractData class to ensure compatibility with the featurizers using data sources. I'm not quite sure how a black box function to the data would work when there is data available in both(could be more in the future) the sources for the same property. Also in my opinion, using the the other source of data in the case of one source missing the require property  seems inconsistent and makes it impossible to track down the source of the discrepant data.",{},,User,False
16231,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-03 06:33:45+00:00,43091756,hackingmaterials/matminer,986759,computron,14116185,hackingmaterials,225872510,298832952,"Hi all,

Just catching up with this thread. I haven't been actively developing or reviewing matminer development because we're trying to push through ""atomate"" at the moment and my full focus (when it's possible for me to code...) is on atomate.

@WardLT - thanks for getting involved with matminer and for your suggestion about normalization. For now I have pulled your PR especially since it helps with setup. In the future it would suggest to separate the PR for setup.py vs the partial RDF but again I am glad that you are taking the time to contribute.

@shyuep - I agree with your implementation suggestions (actually, the get_all_neighbors + numpy histogram method was my suggestion to the original implementor - I guess it was ignored). If @WardLT wants to try that implementation I would be all for it. Otherwise, I will definitely make sure to clean up the code when I get around to making a push for matminer.",{},,User,False
