Thanks!",{},,User,False
16386,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-17 21:27:41+00:00,68483365,graphql-python/graphene-django,1591840,spockNinja,15002022,graphql-python,277789238,352286878,"@igo 

https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene-django/issues/333#issuecomment-348677621

I'm not too sure what you mean by ""cannot be used in a way that it was meant to be used."" Do you mean that there is some documentation out of date, or that you can't accomplish what you need after the upgrade, or something else entirely?

By overriding the resolver for a `DjangoConnectionField`, you have inherited the before/after/first/last arguments so that your resolver does not necessarily have to return a Queryset. Since your resolver could be getting data from anywhere, and should likely be utilizing the backend's mechanism for limits/range, all of the connection parameters could be handled in your new resolver. I'm fairly certain that by returning a queryset, those are still taken care of for you. However, the `**args` method seems like a reasonable approach if you want to ignore the other parameters.

If filtering by slug is the primary use of your custom resolver, you might take a look at http://docs.graphene-python.org/projects/django/en/latest/filtering/",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
