16597,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-11 14:35:10+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,26892988,hanno-arm,16142269,openthread,255883042,335831512,"@hubertmis Thank you. In general, note that you must be prepared to receive a `WANT_READ` or `WANT_WRITE`, even if you call the library in response to an incoming message event or for the purpose of writing. The reason is exactly what we have been discussing, namely that incoming datagrams might entirely consist of unexpected or stale records that are silently discarded. For example, if the Joiner receives the `Change Cipher Spec, Encrypted Handshake, Change Cipher Spec, Encrypted Handshake` combo after the handshake is completed, the subsequent call of `ssl_read` will return `WANT_READ`  because none of the received information is of any use anymore.
Concerning the concrete problem at hand, though, you seem to get the failure from `ssl_write`, which only performs read operation if the handshake is not yet complete - it would therefore be beneficial to understand first if `ssl_write` resp. `Dtls::Send` is indeed only called once the handshake completes. From looking at https://github.com/openthread/openthread/blob/master/src/core/meshcop/dtls.cpp#L141 and https://github.com/openthread/openthread/blob/master/src/core/meshcop/dtls.cpp#L414, I don't know which part of the code would guarantee that, as `Dtls::Process` and therefore also `Dtls::Start` would return without error if the handshake in `Dtls::Process` was paused with a `WANT_READ` or a `WANT_WRITE`. I'm new to your code and don't know where the `Dtls` class is instantiated for use by the joiner, and in particular, where `Dtls::Send` is invoked first after the handshake. Could you point me to that? ",{},NONE,User,False
16598,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-02 23:34:29+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,16142208,jwhui,16142269,openthread,193195948,264591308,"The bootstrap issue is a compatibility issue with automake and newer versions of perl, as noted [here](http://serverfault.com/questions/731539/automake-error-unescaped-left-brace-in-regex-is-deprecated).  You could downgrade to an older version of perl (I'm using 5.18.2).  I'll look into how best to support newer versions of perl.",{},,User,False
16599,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-21 16:55:32+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,16142208,jwhui,16142269,openthread,190482904,261997491,"@LuDuda, I agree that using `GetTimerExpirations()` is more consistent with the rest of the code.  I've updated the code to that.  I also agree that this PR only avoid starting the timer and making a copy of the message on non-router devices.",{},,User,False
