Edouard.",{},MEMBER,User,False
16883,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-07 14:50:56+00:00,63484632,facebookresearch/fastText,10478219,EdouardGrave,16943930,facebookresearch,225917046,342505743,"Hi @arnor-sigurdsson,

The figure is correct, since there is no real distinction between ""context"" and ""input"" words for the skipgram algorithm. Indeed, all words of the sentence will be considered as ""input"" word. Thus, all pairs of words `(w_i, w_j)` such that `|i - j| < ws` will be used as training example, where `w_i` is the ""input"" word and the goal is to predict the ""context"" word `w_j`.

Best,
Edouard",{},MEMBER,User,False
