17128,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-23 23:00:11+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,6504915,bmw,17889013,certbot,201387440,303556430,"The purpose of `patch_get_utility()` is described in more detail in #4010. To give a short summary, we have a lot of places in the code where we do things like [this](https://github.com/certbot/certbot/blob/v0.14.1/certbot/main.py#L263). We use `zope.component.getUtility` to get a display object and then do some kind of user interaction.

The problem is that during our unit tests, these utilities and displays aren't set up so we mock the call. This is fine, however, there are a number of optional parameters to these display objects and some combinations aren't valid. By mocking the call, these assertions never run and we've had code that fails assertions land in `master` because the display object was never properly called because it was mocked out during tests.

`patch_get_utility` mocks out the `getUtility` call, but also runs the assertions on the parameters. The problem identified in the original post of this issue is there is a way `patch_get_utility` causes all of this special functionality to be ignored. This should be fixed.",{},,User,False
17129,IssueCommentEvent,2017-07-17 17:39:00+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,649860,SwartzCr,17889013,certbot,240435262,315826433,"@creepersbane you could try @fyfe's suggestion, but it's also true that certain versions of certbot require certain versions of OpenSSL.
Since python cryptography compiles itself against the system package of python cryptography it comes with specific calls into the cryptography API, based on the version it expects. If cryptography has changed those APIs then it's possible that it'll try calling ones that either don't exist or that have changed name/location. So while you may have OpenSSL - if it's the wrong version for your version of cryptography it could still fail due to the version mismatch.
Let me know once you've tried a few of debugging ideas and let me know how it goes!",{},,User,False
17130,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-09 22:49:16+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,6504915,bmw,17889013,certbot,286148395,364592025,"@jsha, I could use an ACMEv2 sanity check.

Certbot has a flag called `--allow-subset-of-names` which causes it to issue a cert if its able to obtain a valid authz for any of the requested domains. Any domains where Certbot failed DV are removed from the cert. This flag has been controversial and we've considered deprecating/removing it (see #4470), but just to make sure I properly understand our options here, if we wanted to support this flag in ACMEv2, we'd have to create a new order and potentially redo all authorizations correct? (Boulder might automatically reuse authzs, but an arbitrary ACME server might not.)",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
