17424,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-01 14:13:26+00:00,50261113,explosion/sense2vec,13643239,ines,20011530,explosion,327026041,393893427,"> However what about the case when we have a single sentence like ""I went to the bank."" Is there no other way than comparing the Wikipedia list with the tokens to tell that bank is ambiguous?

In our [sense2vec demo](https://explosion.ai/demos/sense2vec), we've added an ""auto"" option that tries to guess the best-matching sense. We do this by simply iterating over the available options and getting the one with the highest frequency. You can [find the relevant bit of code here](https://github.com/explosion/spacy-services/blob/master/sense2vec/app.py#L58).

You could do something similar for your nouns and verbs, and check whether there are other entries for different part-of-speech tags (for example, check for `VERB` if your target word in a `NOUN`). You can then check the frequency and if it's reasonably high, it's a possible homonym. (You definitely want to use a high enough frequency threshold, though – otherwise, it might also turn up entries that got assigned incorrect POS tags. For example, ""cat"" might have been mistakenly tagged as a verb once or twice.)",{},MEMBER,User,False
