17451,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-16 16:18:43+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SoS,9889312,BoPeng,20074389,vatlab,351253910,413602281,"> I'm not sure if I get all the details, but this does not sound good.

The tech details is that we used to keep a separate signature for each input/output file, and we check these files when we create step signatures. md5 were not calculated if the signature already exists. When we switch to database, the target signature database become the busiest one with highest chance of collision and so I removed it in favor of keeping signatures in step signature. These means output files belonging to multiple substeps will be checksumed repeatedly, but ""output belonging to multiple substeps"" is dangerous and generally forbidden in sos. Just think this case

```
input: for_each={'n': range(100)}
output: [f'test_{x}.txt' for x in range(n)]
for file in _output:
    with open(file, 'a') as f:
        f.write(_index)
```
where the next substep will change the output of the previous substeps, so signatures will never work.

> will know to check one file at a time rather than all of them over and over again?

Yes, because there is only one output for each substep. ",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
