18083,IssueCommentEvent,2017-08-11 14:55:19+00:00,34138622,jupyter-widgets/ipywidgets,2397974,SylvainCorlay,25869250,jupyter-widgets,249643068,321835829,👍 ,{},,User,False
18084,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-14 17:33:59+00:00,34138622,jupyter-widgets/ipywidgets,192614,jasongrout,25869250,jupyter-widgets,235920045,308503665,"The root of the issue was a mismatch between the python and js versions. The `data.state` was just the first incompatibility you saw. Since we don't implement the version check when the notebook starts up anymore (it had architecture flaws), the ipywidgets 6 that you had installed would have always printed that error message.

First and foremost we should have clear docs about clearing out old widget versions and installing fresh. A question is if we should put in some javascript code that attempts to detect if the installation is corrupted, and if so, what kinds of checks we can make. I'll think about this - open to ideas or PRs too!",{},,User,False
