18110,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-09 08:00:32+00:00,79083614,python-trio/trio,609896,njsmith,26335827,python-trio,241684970,328261908,"There are some fun error cases to handle.

If some wait setup call errors, then you have to go and abort all the previous wait setup calls to unwind

One way a wait setup call can error is if the same task is trying to wait twice on the same event, e.g. trying to simultaneously put two items into the same queue. Or how should this be handled? The annoying thing is that if we just iterate through the `nowait` versions first, and one of them succeeds, then we'll never notice that the two actions conflict. OTOH it seems difficult to make this succeed for the `wait` case, because who wants to deal with the complications and overhead of using a `MultiDict` to keep track of waiting tasks e.g. I guess the intermediate option would be to silently throw one of them away, but making this work with abort logic might be tricky.",{},OWNER,User,False
