18215,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-19 05:28:24+00:00,76406837,pyecore/pyecore,84800,jean,28776027,pyecore,233195447,309342154,"@moltob thanks again :-) It sounds like you enjoy this modelling stuff. 

> what you meant by the _deep end_.

As soon as there's more than one ""meta"" in play, it's deep, as far as I'm concerned.

> Do you already have Python classes for the different UML types like class or association?

No Python in the picture sadly. (Actually right now I'm generating XML from ad hoc YAML using Python `etree`, but my goal isn't Python-related.)

> Alternatively, you could use the pymultigen project (basis for pyecoregen) to build a code generator for a model-to-text (UML objects to XML file) transformation.

This sounds good. 

> Your UML class instances probably represent some form of business entities.

Yes, exactly.

> If your UML model is not even in memory, but represented as text, you need to use a parser (or write one) to get a memory representation of it and then continue as above.

Yes. The starting point that I'm currently looking at is PlantUML or YUML format for plaintext representation of UML. 

This fulfils two main goals: 

- it gets us a compact plaintext representation with only the salient details and no boilerplate code, checked into version control, and, as a nice extra,
- pretty diagrams, easily shareable on the web, with an interesting range of tool support. 

I don't want to foist any big UML editor onto our company, which currently doesn't use UML in any way shape or form.
I just want to write down our content types in a less ad hoc manner than YAML.

This led to the thought that if I'm going to be parsing PlantUML text, it's probably better to transform it to XMI, and then do a transformation from XMI to Orchard XML. 
Because then I could build on existing XMI tooling, and play with big UML editors too.
I'm not yet sure that this is really a good idea.

> But when you say CMS, web applications usually come with their templating environments,

My specific goal is to generate XML representing content type definitions for the Orchard CMS to import. The Orchard import format is flexible, allowing me to define new types and parts, or to customize standard ones, with all their fields, widgets, and relationships defined, and also to define ""parts"". Parts are similar to interfaces. They add fields and configuration to the content types where they are assigned, and can trigger behaviour (e.g. add a `CommentPart` and people can comment on your new type).
",{},,User,False
